<div id="review_3690985700" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3690985700" />
    <a title="Rykel R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/114923257-rykel-r"><img alt="Rykel R" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616354643p2/114923257.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3690985700?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rykel R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rykel R" href="/user/show/114923257-rykel-r">Rykel R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3690985700" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7908073024448761807">My introduction to Chinua Achebe&apos;s writing happened during my gap year before university. I had just graduated secondary school with a national scholarship to pursue a degree in science. But frankly, I felt disillusioned by the post-colonial education system that afforded me the opportunity to further my education, as well as paralyzed by the prospects of commiting myself to a single path. The first book of Achebe&apos;s I read was Things Fall Apart (the first of his African Trilogy). That book in so</span>
  <span id="freeText7908073024448761807" style="display:none">My introduction to Chinua Achebe's writing happened during my gap year before university. I had just graduated secondary school with a national scholarship to pursue a degree in science. But frankly, I felt disillusioned by the post-colonial education system that afforded me the opportunity to further my education, as well as paralyzed by the prospects of commiting myself to a single path. The first book of Achebe's I read was Things Fall Apart (the first of his African Trilogy). That book in some peculiar way helped shape my early adulthood. <br /><br />There is an embedded wisdom present in Achebe's natural talent for story-telling. There is a sincerity and honesty in the way he portrays life on a continent, that has been distorted (far before his time ) by the Western gaze. A Man of the People, feels decidedly different from the other works of his I've read but it is no less a masterful short novel. You have here true political satire, both nuanced and heavy handed. Set in a fictional African state, the political drama is told from the point of view of a young man, himself a university graduate-- who through youthful idealism, ambition and some hurt feelings, takes on a corrupt incumbent government. <br /><br />From the fervour of populism, to fair-weathered party allegiance, social apathy and anti-intellectualism, there are lots of comparisons to be made with the sort of political landscape present in the Caribbean. I found myself laughing and nodding at the similarities, facilitated by the droll and conspiratorial voice of the narrator.<br /><br />Don't start with this novel if you're interested in Chinua's writing. Things Fall Apart is *the* intro to his work or if you're in the mood for a rapier-like critical essay, read An Image of Africa. You'll easily return to this one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7908073024448761807" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

