<div id="review_1044446238" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1044446238" />
    <a title="Grace" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29376003-grace"><img alt="Grace" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612671399p2/29376003.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1044446238?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Grace" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Grace" href="/user/show/29376003-grace">Grace</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1044446238" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6532889249693052262">A gripping tale, with vividly described characters like the bootlicking Nwege, Edna&apos;s greedy, avaricious father, the absurdly hilarious chief Koko, and Odili&apos;s own proud, well known and widely hated Father, Hezekiah. This story chronicles the politics of African states, and it&apos;s eat-and-let-eat leaders. I read this book 11 years ago in school and I can probably remember it word for word, a must read for anyone seeking insight into the very nature of African state of affairs, from overnight infla</span>
  <span id="freeText6532889249693052262" style="display:none">A gripping tale, with vividly described characters like the bootlicking Nwege, Edna's greedy, avaricious father, the absurdly hilarious chief Koko, and Odili's own proud, well known and widely hated Father, Hezekiah. This story chronicles the politics of African states, and it's eat-and-let-eat leaders. I read this book 11 years ago in school and I can probably remember it word for word, a must read for anyone seeking insight into the very nature of African state of affairs, from overnight inflation to the disillusion poverty brings, and the rise of unknown backbenchers who will support unpopular motions in parliament if only for personal gain. Achebe tells this tale with multiple hilarious references, and makes even the most mundane story come through with such a fine mastery of humor. A thought provoking read.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6532889249693052262" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


